WITH 
 workspace as (
      SELECT
      account_id,
      workspace_id, 
      workspace_name,
      workspace_url,
      status,
      concat(COALESCE(workspace_name, ''), ' (id: ', workspace_id, ')') AS workspace_full_name
      FROM system.access.workspaces_latest
      WHERE
      (array_contains(:param_workspace, concat(COALESCE(workspace_name, ''), ' (id: ', workspace_id, ')')) OR array_contains(:param_workspace,'all'))
),

raw_history AS (
    SELECT
        f.*,
        CASE 
            WHEN QueryRuntimeSeconds >= CAST(:long_running_seconds_treshold AS FLOAT) 
            THEN 'Long Running' 
            ELSE 'Short Running' 
        END AS LongRunningQueryFlag,
        CASE 
            WHEN QueryRuntimeSeconds >= CAST(:long_running_seconds_treshold AS FLOAT) 
            THEN 1 
            ELSE 0 
        END AS Calc_LongRunningQueryFlag,
        workspace_name,
        workspace_url
    FROM main.dbsql_warehouse_advisor.warehouse_query_history f
    INNER JOIN workspace
    on f.workspace_id = workspace.workspace_id
    WHERE 
    f.warehouse_id IN (
            SELECT DISTINCT warehouse_id 
            FROM system.compute.warehouses AS c
            WHERE (array_contains(:warehouse_name, CONCAT(c.warehouse_name, ' (id:', c.warehouse_id, ')'))) -- all loads TOO much data to client  OR array_contains(:warehouse_name,'all')
        )
        AND start_time BETWEEN CAST(:time_range.min AS TIMESTAMP) AND CAST(:time_range.max AS TIMESTAMP)
),

current_warehouses AS (
  SELECT warehouse_id,
  warehouse_name,
  CONCAT(w.warehouse_name, ' (id:', w.warehouse_id, ')') AS clean_warehouse_name,
  workspace_id,
  account_id,
  change_time,
  delete_time,
  warehouse_type,
  warehouse_channel,
  warehouse_size,
  min_clusters,
  max_clusters,
  auto_stop_minutes,
  tags,
  CASE WHEN delete_time IS NOT NULL THEN 'Deleted' ELSE 'Active' END AS is_deleted
  FROM system.compute.warehouses w
  WHERE
    -- workspace filter
    (array_contains(:workspace_id,w.workspace_id) OR array_contains(:workspace_id,'all'))
  -- warehouse filter
    AND (array_contains(:warehouse_name, CONCAT(w.warehouse_name, ' (id:', w.warehouse_id, ')')) OR array_contains(:warehouse_name,'all'))
  QUALIFY ROW_NUMBER() OVER (PARTITION BY workspace_id, warehouse_id ORDER BY change_time DESC) == 1 -- Get more recent snapshot
),

px_all AS (
    SELECT DISTINCT
        sku_name,
        pricing.default AS unit_price,
        CAST(unit_price AS DECIMAL(10,3)) AS sku_price
    FROM system.billing.list_prices 
    QUALIFY ROW_NUMBER() OVER (PARTITION BY sku_name ORDER BY price_start_time DESC) = 1
),

history AS (
    SELECT *,
        CASE WHEN :include_metadata = 'No' THEN SUM(TotalResourceTimeUsedForAllocation) OVER ()
            WHEN :include_metadata = 'Yes' THEN SUM(TotalResourceTimeUsedForAllocationWithMetadata) OVER ()
        END AS TotalUsedTimeInWarehouse,

         CASE WHEN :include_metadata = 'No' THEN SUM(COALESCE(TotalResourceTimeUsedForAllocation, 0)) OVER (PARTITION BY statement_text)
            WHEN :include_metadata = 'Yes' THEN SUM(COALESCE(TotalResourceTimeUsedForAllocationWithMetadata, 0)) OVER (PARTITION BY statement_text)
        END AS TotalStatementTextTimeUsed,

        CASE 
            WHEN TotalUsedTimeInWarehouse = 0 THEN NULL 
            ELSE TotalResourceTimeUsedForAllocation / TotalUsedTimeInWarehouse 
        END AS ProportionOfWarehouseTimeUsedByQuery
    FROM raw_history
),

filtered_warehouse_usage AS (
    WITH trimmed_usage AS (
        SELECT 
            TIMESTAMPDIFF(SECOND, usage_start_time, CAST(:time_range.min AS TIMESTAMP)) AS seconds_before_start_range,
            TIMESTAMPDIFF(SECOND, usage_start_time, usage_end_time) AS full_start_range_length,
            TIMESTAMPDIFF(SECOND, GREATEST(CAST(:time_range.min AS TIMESTAMP), usage_start_time), usage_end_time) AS seconds_remaining_in_original_start_range,
            GREATEST(CAST(:time_range.min AS TIMESTAMP), usage_start_time) AS trimmed_start_time,
            LEAST(CAST(:time_range.max AS TIMESTAMP), usage_end_time) AS trimmed_end_time,
            TIMESTAMPDIFF(SECOND, LEAST(CAST(:time_range.max AS TIMESTAMP), usage_end_time), usage_end_time) AS seconds_after_end_range,
            TIMESTAMPDIFF(SECOND, usage_start_time, usage_end_time) AS full_end_range_length,
            CASE 
                WHEN full_start_range_length > 0 
                THEN COALESCE((full_start_range_length - seconds_before_start_range) / full_start_range_length, 0) 
                ELSE NULL 
            END AS StartTrimProportion,
            CASE 
                WHEN full_end_range_length > 0 
                THEN COALESCE((full_end_range_length - seconds_after_end_range) / full_end_range_length, 0) 
                ELSE NULL 
            END AS EndTrimProportion,
            COALESCE(EndTrimProportion, StartTrimProportion, 1) AS TrimProportion,
            u.usage_start_time,
            u.usage_end_time,
            u.usage_quantity AS dbus,
            u.warehouse_id AS warehouse_id,
            (CAST(px.sku_price AS FLOAT) * (1 - CAST(:dbsql_discount AS FLOAT)) * dbus) AS UsageDollars
        FROM main.dbsql_warehouse_advisor.warehouse_usage AS u
        INNER JOIN px_all AS px 
            ON px.sku_name = u.sku_name
        WHERE 
            (u.warehouse_id IN (
                SELECT DISTINCT warehouse_id 
                FROM current_warehouses
            )
            )
            AND usage_unit = 'DBU'
            AND (
                (usage_start_time BETWEEN CAST(:time_range.min AS TIMESTAMP) AND CAST(:time_range.max AS TIMESTAMP))
                OR (usage_end_time BETWEEN CAST(:time_range.min AS TIMESTAMP) AND CAST(:time_range.max AS TIMESTAMP))
            )
    )
    SELECT 
        warehouse_id,
        SUM(dbus * TrimProportion) AS Total_Warehouse_Period_DBUs,
        SUM(UsageDollars * TrimProportion) AS Total_Warehouse_Period_Dollars
    FROM trimmed_usage
    GROUP BY warehouse_id
),

warehouse_average_ratio_metrics AS (
    SELECT 
        warehouse_id,
        COALESCE(AVG(CAST(CPUTotalExecutionTime AS FLOAT)) / AVG(CAST(QueryRuntimeSeconds AS FLOAT)), 0) AS WarehouseAvgTaskSkewRatio,
        COALESCE(MAX(CPUTotalExecutionTime) / MAX(QueryRuntimeSeconds), 0) AS WarehouseMaxTaskSkewRatio
    FROM history
    WHERE CPUTotalExecutionTime > 0 AND ReadDataAmountInGB > 0
    AND execution_status NOT IN ('FAILED')
    GROUP BY warehouse_id
),

query_level_intel_metrics AS (
    SELECT qh.*,
        w.WarehouseAvgTaskSkewRatio AS WarehouseAvgTaskToExecutionTimeRatio,
        CASE 
            WHEN CPUTotalExecutionTime > 0 
            AND ReadDataAmountInGB > 0 
            AND execution_status NOT IN ('FAILED')
            THEN qh.QueryRuntimeSeconds / (qh.CPUTotalExecutionTime / w.WarehouseAvgTaskSkewRatio)
            ELSE NULL
        END AS QueryEfficiencyRatio,
        u.Total_Warehouse_Period_Dollars,
        (u.Total_Warehouse_Period_Dollars * ProportionOfWarehouseTimeUsedByQuery) AS AllocatedQueryCostByTime
    FROM history AS qh
    LEFT JOIN warehouse_average_ratio_metrics AS w ON w.warehouse_id = qh.warehouse_id
    LEFT JOIN filtered_warehouse_usage AS u ON u.warehouse_id = qh.warehouse_id
)

SELECT 
    z.*,
    -- Performance Flags
    CASE 
        WHEN ReadDataAmountInGB > CAST(:data_volume_min_gb AS FLOAT)
        THEN 'High Volume Read' 
        ELSE 'FINE' 
    END AS HighDataVolumeFlag,
        CASE 
        WHEN WrittenDataAmountInGB > CAST(:data_volume_min_gb AS FLOAT)
        THEN 'High Volume Written' 
        ELSE 'FINE' 
    END AS HighDataWritesVolumeFlag,
-- Queuing
    CASE 
        WHEN ProportionQueueTime > CAST(:queue_proportion_threshold AS FLOAT)
        THEN 'High Queue Time' 
        ELSE 'FINE' 
    END AS HighQueueingTimeFlag,
-- Result Fetch
    CASE 
        WHEN  ProportionResultFetchTime > CAST(:result_proportion_threshold AS FLOAT)
        THEN 'High Result Fetch Time' 
        ELSE 'FINE' 
    END AS HighResultFetchTimeFlag,
    CASE 
        WHEN LENGTH(raw_tagged) >= 1 THEN raw_tagged 
        ELSE 'Untagged' 
    END AS QueryTag,

    CASE
    WHEN query_source_type = 'JOB' THEN CONCAT('/jobs/', query_source_id)
    WHEN query_source_type = 'SQL QUERY' THEN CONCAT('/sql/queries/', query_source_id)
    WHEN query_source_type = 'AI/BI DASHBOARD' THEN CONCAT('/sql/dashboardsv3/', query_source_id)
    WHEN query_source_type = 'LEGACY DASHBOARD' THEN CONCAT('/sql/dashboards/', query_source_id)
    WHEN query_source_type = 'ALERTS' THEN CONCAT('/sql/alerts/', query_source_id)
    WHEN query_source_type = 'GENIE SPACE' THEN CONCAT('/genie/rooms/', query_source_id)
    WHEN query_source_type = 'NOTEBOOK' THEN CONCAT('/editor/notebooks/', query_source_id)
    ELSE ''
  END as url_helper,
  CONCAT('/sql/history?uiQueryProfileVisible=true&queryId=', statement_id) AS query_profile_url,
    -- Warehouse-level event info
    current_warehouses.warehouse_name,
    current_warehouses.clean_warehouse_name,
    current_warehouses.warehouse_type,
    current_warehouses.warehouse_channel,
    current_warehouses.warehouse_size,
    current_warehouses.min_clusters,
    current_warehouses.max_clusters,
    current_warehouses.auto_stop_minutes,
    current_warehouses.tags,
    current_warehouses.change_time,
    current_warehouses.delete_time,
TIMESTAMPDIFF(SECOND, :time_range.min, :time_range.max) AS total_window_seconds,
TIMESTAMPDIFF(MINUTE, :time_range.min, :time_range.max) AS total_window_minutes,
:time_range.min AS min_time_window,
:time_range.max AS max_time_window,
-- cleaning performance on queue time distribution
CASE WHEN proportionqueuetime > 1 THEN 1 ELSE round(proportionqueuetime, 1) END AS rounded_proportion_queue_time,
CASE WHEN :group_key = 'Query Source Type' THEN query_source_type
     WHEN :group_key = 'Execution Status' THEN execution_status
     WHEN :group_key = 'Statement Type' THEN statement_type
     WHEN :group_key = 'Warehouse' THEN clean_warehouse_name
     WHEN :group_key = 'Workspace Id' THEN z.workspace_id
     WHEN :group_key = 'Query Source Id' THEN query_source_id
END AS group_key,
case
        when :param_time_key = 'Year' then date_trunc('YEAR', start_time)
        when :param_time_key = 'Quarter' then date_trunc('QUARTER', start_time)
        when :param_time_key = 'Month' then date_trunc('MONTH', start_time)
        when :param_time_key = 'Week' then date_trunc('WEEK', start_time)
        when :param_time_key = 'Day' then date_trunc('DAY', start_time)
        when :param_time_key = 'Hour' then date_trunc('HOUR', start_time)
        else start_time
      end as time_key,
CASE WHEN SpilledDataAmountInGB > 0 THEN 1 ELSE 0 END AS SpillMeasureFlag
FROM query_level_intel_metrics AS z
LEFT JOIN current_warehouses AS current_warehouses ON current_warehouses.warehouse_id = z.warehouse_id

-- Most recent warehouse config in selected time period
WITH  
 workspace as (
      SELECT
      account_id,
      workspace_id, 
      workspace_name,
      workspace_url,
      status,
      concat(COALESCE(workspace_name, ''), ' (id: ', workspace_id, ')') AS workspace_full_name
      FROM system.access.workspaces_latest
      WHERE
      (array_contains(:param_workspace, concat(COALESCE(workspace_name, ''), ' (id: ', workspace_id, ')')) OR array_contains(:param_workspace,'all'))
),

warehouse_snapshot AS (
  SELECT warehouse_id,
  CONCAT(w.warehouse_name, ' (id:', w.warehouse_id, ')') AS warehouse_name,
  w.workspace_id,
  workspace_name,
  w.account_id,
  change_time,
  delete_time,
  warehouse_channel,
    warehouse_type,
    warehouse_size,
    min_clusters,
    max_clusters,
    auto_stop_minutes,
  CASE WHEN delete_time IS NOT NULL THEN 'Deleted' ELSE 'Active' END AS is_deleted
  FROM system.compute.warehouses w
  INNER JOIN workspace
    on w.workspace_id = workspace.workspace_id
  WHERE
  -- warehouse filter
   (array_contains(:warehouse_name, CONCAT(w.warehouse_name, ' (id:', w.warehouse_id, ')')) OR array_contains(:warehouse_name,'all')) -- TEST OR warehouse_id = 'be0970625877facc'
  QUALIFY ROW_NUMBER() OVER (PARTITION BY w.workspace_id, warehouse_id ORDER BY change_time DESC) == 1 -- Get more recent snapshot
),


raw_scaling AS (
    SELECT 
        DATE_TRUNC('MINUTE', w.event_time) AS event_minute,
        MAX_BY(w.cluster_count, w.event_time) AS clusters,
        MAX(w.warehouse_id) AS warehouse_id
    FROM main.dbsql_warehouse_advisor.warehouse_scaling_events w
    INNER JOIN warehouse_snapshot c 
        ON w.warehouse_id = c.warehouse_id
    WHERE w.event_time BETWEEN CAST(:time_range.min AS TIMESTAMP) AND CAST(:time_range.max AS TIMESTAMP)
    AND event_type IN ('RUNNING', 'SCALED_UP', 'SCALED_DOWN', 'STOPPED')
    GROUP BY DATE_TRUNC('MINUTE', w.event_time)
    ORDER BY event_minute
),


full_series AS (
SELECT explode(sequence((SELECT MIN(event_minute) FROM raw_scaling), (SELECT MAX(event_minute) FROM raw_scaling), INTERVAL 1 MINUTE)) AS minuteChunk
),


filled_in_series AS (
    SELECT 
        spine.minuteChunk AS event_minute,
        MAX(s2.clusters) AS NumberOfClustersOn,
        MAX(s2.warehouse_id) AS warehouse_id
    FROM full_series AS spine
    LEFT JOIN raw_scaling AS s2 
        ON DATE_TRUNC('MINUTE', s2.event_minute) = spine.minuteChunk
    GROUP BY spine.minuteChunk
    ORDER BY event_minute
),

final_scale AS (
SELECT event_minute,
LAST_VALUE(NumberOfClustersOn, true) OVER (ORDER BY event_minute) AS NumberOfClustersOn,
LAST_VALUE(w.warehouse_id, true) OVER (ORDER BY event_minute)  AS warehouse_id
 FROM filled_in_series  w
 ORDER BY warehouse_id, event_minute
)

SELECT 
f.*,
warehouse_channel,
warehouse_type,
warehouse_size,
min_clusters AS warehouse_min_clusters,
max_clusters AS warehouse_max_clusters,
auto_stop_minutes AS warehouse_auto_stop_min,
case
        when :param_time_key = 'Year' then date_trunc('YEAR', event_minute)
        when :param_time_key = 'Quarter' then date_trunc('QUARTER', event_minute)
        when :param_time_key = 'Month' then date_trunc('MONTH', event_minute)
        when :param_time_key = 'Week' then date_trunc('WEEK', event_minute)
        when :param_time_key = 'Day' then date_trunc('DAY', event_minute)
        when :param_time_key = 'Hour' then date_trunc('HOUR', event_minute)
        else event_minute
      end as time_key
FROM final_scale AS f
LEFT JOIN warehouse_snapshot c ON f.warehouse_id = c.warehouse_id

WITH
 workspace as (

      concat(COALESCE(workspace_name, ''), ' (id: ', workspace_id, ')') AS workspace_full_name
      FROM system.access.workspaces_latest
      WHERE
      (array_contains(:param_workspace, concat(COALESCE(workspace_name, ''), ' (id: ', workspace_id, ')')) OR array_contains(:param_workspace,'all'))
),

warehouse_snapshot AS (
  SELECT warehouse_id,
  CONCAT(w.warehouse_name, ' (id:', w.warehouse_id, ')') AS warehouse_name,
  w.workspace_id,
  w.account_id,
  change_time,
  delete_time,
  warehouse_channel,
    warehouse_type,
    warehouse_size,
    min_clusters,
    max_clusters,
    auto_stop_minutes,
  CASE WHEN delete_time IS NOT NULL THEN 'Deleted' ELSE 'Active' END AS is_deleted
  FROM system.compute.warehouses w
  INNER JOIN workspace ON w.workspace_id = workspace.workspace_id
  WHERE
  -- warehouse filter
 (array_contains(:warehouse_name, CONCAT(w.warehouse_name, ' (id:', w.warehouse_id, ')')) OR array_contains(:warehouse_name,'all')) -- TEST OR warehouse_id = 'be0970625877facc'
  QUALIFY ROW_NUMBER() OVER (PARTITION BY w.workspace_id, warehouse_id ORDER BY change_time DESC) == 1 -- Get more recent snapshot
),



px_all AS (
    SELECT DISTINCT
        sku_name,
        pricing.default AS unit_price,
        CAST(unit_price AS DECIMAL(10,3)) AS sku_price
    FROM system.billing.list_prices 
    QUALIFY ROW_NUMBER() OVER (PARTITION BY sku_name ORDER BY price_start_time DESC) = 1
),

raw_history AS (
    SELECT * 
    FROM main.dbsql_warehouse_advisor.warehouse_query_history f
    WHERE 
    f.warehouse_id IN  (
            SELECT DISTINCT warehouse_id FROM warehouse_snapshot
        )
    AND start_time >= CAST(:time_range.min AS TIMESTAMP) 
    AND end_time <= CAST(:time_range.max AS TIMESTAMP) 
    AND QueryWork > 0 -- This is how query cost is defined
    AND statement_type IS NOT NULL
),

warehouse_time as (
  select
    warehouse_id,
         SUM(COALESCE(TotalResourceTimeUsedForAllocationWithMetadata, 0))
         as TotalUsedTimeInWarehouse
  from
    raw_history
  group by
    warehouse_id
),

history AS (
  SELECT
    a.*,
    b.TotalUsedTimeInWarehouse,
         SUM(COALESCE(TotalResourceTimeUsedForAllocationWithMetadata, 0)) OVER (PARTITION BY statement_text)
        AS TotalStatementTextTimeUsed,

        CASE 
            WHEN TotalUsedTimeInWarehouse = 0 THEN NULL 
            ELSE TotalResourceTimeUsedForAllocation / TotalUsedTimeInWarehouse 
        END AS ProportionOfWarehouseTimeUsedByQuery
  FROM
    raw_history a
    inner join warehouse_time b on a.warehouse_id = b.warehouse_id
),
-- Partition cost allocation by warehouse so you can look at multiple warehouses at once

filtered_warehouse_usage AS (
    WITH trimmed_usage AS (
        SELECT 
            TIMESTAMPDIFF(SECOND, usage_start_time, CAST(:time_range.min AS TIMESTAMP)) AS seconds_before_start_range,
            TIMESTAMPDIFF(SECOND, usage_start_time, usage_end_time) AS full_start_range_length,
            full_start_range_length - seconds_before_start_range AS seconds_remaining_in_original_start_range,
            GREATEST(CAST(:time_range.min AS TIMESTAMP), usage_start_time) AS trimmed_start_time,
            LEAST(CAST(:time_range.max AS TIMESTAMP), usage_end_time) AS trimmed_end_time,
            TIMESTAMPDIFF(SECOND, CAST(:time_range.max AS TIMESTAMP), usage_end_time) AS seconds_after_end_range,
            TIMESTAMPDIFF(SECOND, usage_start_time, usage_end_time) AS full_end_range_length,
            full_end_range_length - seconds_after_end_range AS seconds_remaining_in_original_end_range,

            CASE 
                WHEN seconds_before_start_range > 0 
                THEN COALESCE((full_start_range_length - seconds_before_start_range) / full_start_range_length, 0) 
                ELSE NULL 
            END AS StartTrimProportion,
            CASE 
                WHEN seconds_after_end_range > 0 
                THEN COALESCE((full_start_range_length - seconds_after_end_range) / full_start_range_length, 0) 
                ELSE NULL 
            END AS EndTrimProportion,
            COALESCE(EndTrimProportion, StartTrimProportion, 1) AS TrimProportion,
            u.usage_start_time,
            u.usage_end_time,
            u.usage_quantity AS dbus,
            u.warehouse_id AS warehouse_id,
            (CAST(px.sku_price AS FLOAT) * (1 - CAST(:dbsql_discount AS FLOAT)) * dbus) AS UsageDollars
        FROM main.dbsql_warehouse_advisor.warehouse_usage AS u
        INNER JOIN px_all AS px 
            ON px.sku_name = u.sku_name
        WHERE 
            usage_unit = 'DBU'
            AND (
                usage_start_time BETWEEN CAST(:time_range.min AS TIMESTAMP) AND CAST(:time_range.max AS TIMESTAMP)
                OR usage_end_time BETWEEN CAST(:time_range.min AS TIMESTAMP) AND CAST(:time_range.max AS TIMESTAMP)
            )
    )
    SELECT 
        u.warehouse_id,
        SUM(u.dbus * TrimProportion) AS Total_Warehouse_Period_DBUs,
        SUM(u.UsageDollars * TrimProportion) AS Total_Warehouse_Period_Dollars
        -- Insert idle proportion here?
    FROM trimmed_usage AS u
    GROUP BY warehouse_id
),

history_with_pricing AS (
    SELECT 
        h1.*,
        wh.Total_Warehouse_Period_DBUs, 
        wh.Total_Warehouse_Period_Dollars
    FROM history AS h1
    LEFT JOIN filtered_warehouse_usage AS wh 
        ON h1.warehouse_id = wh.warehouse_id
),

query_proportion_agg AS (
    SELECT 
        SHA2(REGEXP_REPLACE(REGEXP_REPLACE(REGEXP_REPLACE(statement_text, '/\\*.*?\\*/', ''), '(--[^\\n]*)', ''), ' ', ''), 256) AS query_signature,
        workspace_id, 
        warehouse_id,
        MAX(statement_text) AS statement_text,
        MAX(statement_type) AS statetment_type,
        MIN(start_time) AS FirstRunInPeriod,
        MAX(start_time) AS LatestRunInPeriod,
        MAX(raw_tagged) AS raw_tagged,
        MAX(dbt_app) AS dbt_app,
        MAX(dbt_node_id) AS dbt_node_id,
        MAX(dbt_profile_name) AS dbt_profile_id,
        MAX(dbt_target_name) AS dbt_target_name,
        MAX(dbt_version) AS dbt_version,
        MAX(IsDBTQuery) AS IsDBTQuery,
        FIRST(parsed_dbt_comment) AS parsed_dbt_comment,
        COUNT(statement_id) AS NumberOfExecutions,
        AVG(QueryRuntimeSeconds) AS AvgRuntimeInSeconds,
        MAX(TotalUsedTimeInWarehouse) AS TotalWarehouseTimeUsed,
        MAX(Total_Warehouse_Period_DBUs) AS Total_Warehouse_Period_DBUs,
        MAX(Total_Warehouse_Period_Dollars) AS Total_Warehouse_Period_Dollars,
        SUM(TotalResourceTimeUsedForAllocation) AS TotalStatementTimeUsed,
        ARRAY_DISTINCT(COLLECT_LIST(NAMED_STRUCT('user', executed_by, 'execution_count', 
            (SELECT COUNT(statement_id) FROM history AS in_hist 
             WHERE in_hist.executed_by = u.executed_by AND in_hist.statement_text = u.statement_text)
        ))) AS UserRunCounts
    FROM history_with_pricing AS u
    GROUP BY query_signature, workspace_id, warehouse_id
),

statement_attribution AS (
    SELECT 
        a.*,
        CASE 
            WHEN TotalWarehouseTimeUsed = 0 THEN NULL 
            ELSE TotalStatementTimeUsed / TotalWarehouseTimeUsed 
        END AS StatementTaskTimeProportion,
        -- Add Idle here
        Total_Warehouse_Period_Dollars * StatementTaskTimeProportion AS StatementAllocatedDollars,
        Total_Warehouse_Period_DBUs * StatementTaskTimeProportion AS StatementAllocatedDBUs
    FROM query_proportion_agg a
),

statement_rollup_cumulative_sum AS (
    SELECT 
        *,

),


raw_scaling AS (
    SELECT 
        DATE_TRUNC('MINUTE', w.event_time) AS event_minute,
        MAX_BY(w.cluster_count, w.event_time) AS clusters,
        MAX(w.warehouse_id) AS warehouse_id
    FROM main.dbsql_warehouse_advisor.warehouse_scaling_events w
    INNER JOIN warehouse_snapshot c 
        ON w.warehouse_id = c.warehouse_id
    WHERE w.event_time BETWEEN CAST(:time_range.min AS TIMESTAMP) AND CAST(:time_range.max AS TIMESTAMP)
    AND event_type IN ('RUNNING', 'SCALED_UP', 'SCALED_DOWN', 'STOPPED')
    GROUP BY DATE_TRUNC('MINUTE', w.event_time)
    ORDER BY event_minute
),

full_series AS (
    SELECT explode(sequence((SELECT MIN(event_minute) FROM raw_scaling), (SELECT MAX(event_minute) FROM raw_scaling), INTERVAL 1 MINUTE)) AS minuteChunk
),

filled_in_series AS (
    SELECT 
        spine.minuteChunk AS event_minute,
        MAX(s2.clusters) AS NumberOfClustersOn,
        MAX(s2.warehouse_id) AS warehouse_id
    FROM full_series AS spine
    LEFT JOIN raw_scaling AS s2 
        ON DATE_TRUNC('MINUTE', s2.event_minute) = spine.minuteChunk
    GROUP BY spine.minuteChunk
    ORDER BY event_minute
),

final_scale AS (
    SELECT event_minute,
        case
        when :param_time_key = 'Year' then date_trunc('YEAR', event_minute)
        when :param_time_key = 'Quarter' then date_trunc('QUARTER', event_minute)
        when :param_time_key = 'Month' then date_trunc('MONTH', event_minute)
        when :param_time_key = 'Week' then date_trunc('WEEK', event_minute)
        when :param_time_key = 'Day' then date_trunc('DAY', event_minute)
        when :param_time_key = 'Hour' then date_trunc('HOUR', event_minute)
        else event_minute
      end as time_key,
    LAST_VALUE(NumberOfClustersOn, true) OVER (ORDER BY event_minute) AS NumberOfClustersOn,
    LAST_VALUE(w.warehouse_id, true) OVER (ORDER BY event_minute)  AS warehouse_id
    FROM filled_in_series  w
    ORDER BY warehouse_id, event_minute
)

    NumberOfClustersOn,
    COUNT(*) AS total_minutes
FROM final_scale
GROUP BY time_key, NumberOfClustersOn

# DBSQL Warehouse Advisor
-----

## Sections
1. Warehouse Usage- show basic billing usage and cost metrics for a warehouse (dbus, $, over time)
2. Scaling Patterns - shows basic scaling metrics per warehouse (scaling history, avg scale (weighted))
3. Performance Advisor - Show common query history metrics such as runtime, queue time, peak queuing, failure rate, cache %, etc., identify inefficient queries with skew/spill indicators
4. Query Statement Level Resource Allocation Advisor - Identify and allocate warehouse total used time by statement and query (optionally include and aggregate by TAG)

## Section 1 - Warehouse Usage
-----
This section shows basic warehouse usage over time across the account. It also provides a table showing the changes / edits to a warehouse over time

#### Key Terms & Definitions
-----
1. DBSQL Discount % - this is a parameter that allows a user to input their own discount rates for all DBSQL SKUs into the dashboard to get a more accurate picture of warehouse costs. The system tables currently show all prices at list rate, so this helps resolve custom discounts for DBSQL.

## Section 2 - Scaling Patterns
-----
This section shows summary metrics for how the warehouse scales for concurrency in a particular period of time. Common use cases for this section include workload capacity planning, scaling efficiency change monitoring (i.e. create an alert when warehouse scales above 1 cluster for longer than 5% of my day), as well as performance troubleshooting. 

#### Key Terms & Definitions
-----
1. "Mintues on Cluster N" - this is a summary metric for describing how much time a warehouse spent scaled at a specified level of concurrency. This is used for building weighted demand plans for spiky concurrency workloads more accurately.

## Section 3 - Performance Advisor
-----
This section helps dive into warehouse performance to understand how well the warehouse is performing against SLAs, identifying bottlenecks, as well as queries that are taking up the majority of the resources.

#### Key Terms & Definitions
-----
1. Query Runtime (P50, 75, 95, 99) - The distribution metrics of query runtime. This is the metric used to measure SLAs
2. % Query Queue Time - The proportion of a query's total runtime that was spent in the queue. This is a valuable metric to normalized for wasted time queueing for both short and long queries. 
3. Queue Time - The amount of time queries are spending in the queue. This can vary in importance by the length of the query. 
4. Peak Queued / Peak Running - This represents the maximum number of queries queued or running at a given point in time. 
5. Query Work - This is a non financial metric to measure and compare how "expensive" or "greedy" queries are without doing shared resource allocation (which can be skewed in many scenarios). Query Work is the sum of all steps that require cluster resources. Query Work = execution time + compilation time + result fetching time. 
6. Allocated Query Cost by Time - ALL Query level costs in this dashboard are allocated costs. This means that a warehouse is a shared resource, and allocation the total cost of a warehouse to specific queries / users depends on dividing up the total costs by the amount of query work done. This allows users to loosely attribute dollars back to end users / queries. This is valuable but sensitive to the selected time window and the amount of queries running on a cluster. For example, if I have a warehouse that costs $10 per hour, and I run 1 query that only takes 1 second, then that query will be allocated the whole $10 if no other queries are run. Conversely, if I run 10 queries in that hour, those queries will have that $10 allocated in proportion to the amount of "work" each query took.

## Section 4 - Query Cost Allocation
-----
This section helps users allocate the cost of a warehouse back to the user and query level detail. In this section, you can even attribute shared warehouse costs down to query tags (custom in the data model) as well as DBT model information. This is an ALLOCATION - which means it simply takes the cost of a whole warehouse in the selected time period and attributes that actual cost proportionally to the queries that are run during that time. This is sensitive to the saturation of a warehouse as well as idle time. For example, if I have a warehouse that costs $10 per hour, and I run 1 query that only takes 1 second, then that query will be allocated the whole $10 if no other queries are run. Conversely, if I run 10 queries in that hour, those queries will have that $10 allocated in proportion to the amount of "work" each query took. This is different than query work, which is defined above and is a more reliable deterministic way of finding expensive / greedy queries on a warehouse. 

#### Key Terms & Definitions
-----
1. Query Signature - This is the term for a unique SQL statement that is executed on the warehouse. This is different than a statement_id - which is a globally unique execution of SQL. The query signature rolls multiple statement executions up to a unique SQL string. In the signature - the SQL statement is hash and aggregated, excluding comments in the SQL.

# Overall Warehouses (all) Usage & Info Overview
-----
This section helps users get a simple cost picture for their warehouse over time, as well as obtain a clear picture of momentum of cost over time - which can easily be turned into an alert.

## Key Performance KPIs
This section tracks 4 core KPIS: 

1. Query Runtime (P50, 95,99) - The total runtime (wall clock of a query) - including queueing time
2. Queuing Count (P50,95,99) & Time - The maximum amount of queries in the queue at a given window of time.
3. Queries Spilling to Disk & GBs spilled to disk (P50, 95, 99) - This is the frequency and volume of data spilled to disk to help track warehouse size limits to a query. 
4. GBs Read & Written - This is the amount of data read and written by queries (P50, 95, 99, 100). This is a metric to help understand directionally what cluster size should be chosen.

## Warehouse Performance - Query Runtime SLAs
Query runtime helps identify if your warehouse is meeting your SLAs. The runtime is generally controlled by the size of the warehouse but also influenced by how long queries are spent queued. So if your queries are running slower than your desired SLA, try increasing the warehouse T-shirt size and using the below visual to see if queries are queuing too often.

##### Best Practices: 
The below visuals show overall P95, 99, as well the as P99/95 for each segment of time within the overall selected window. To use this, focus on the overall SLA. If you are NOT meeting your SLA, then you either need to make the warehouse larger or increase concurrency. If your queries runtimes are taking too long and queries are NOT spending an extensive amount of time queuing, then you likely need a bigger warehouse to run the query faster. If your queuing is high, but your average query runtimes are fine, then you likely need to increase concurrency. Lastly, you can also monitor your query spilling (both frequency and amount) to also use as a clear indicator that your warehouse can be larger to get better performance. ## Warehouse Performance - Queuing Metrics
There are 3 key metrics under this section: peak queued, peak running, and % of a query life spent in the queue. 
Peak Queuing shows how many queries get queued before running in a given time window. The MAX peak queued queries in a time window helps show how much more concurrency scaling the warehouse might need to not require queuing. Peak Running shows how many queries are running concurrently at a point in time. % of query life spent in queue shows how much of a query runtime is wasted in the queue - this is a good metric to look at because it normalizes for short and long running queries. 
##### Best Practices: 
Just because there is queuing, does not mean you need to scale up your warehouse. Always scale your warehouses based on the SLA metrics first. If queries are being queued and you still meet your SLA, there is no value in increases concurrency scaling of the warehouse.

## Warehouse Performance - Data Scanning & Disk Spilling Metrics
Data Scanned helps understand how much data queries are reading - this is a decent proxy for warehouse size. Disk Spilling (both frequency and amount) is a clear metrics that helps track the amount of available memory in a cluster relative to the amount of data that needs to be processed in a given query.

##### Best Practices: 
Spilling to disk occasionally is completely fine, but when this happens consistently and the data volume of spilling is high (many many GBs/TBs), then it becomes highly likely that a larger warehouse is more performant AND cost effective.  When the % of queries spilling to disk increases, that is a clear sign the warehouse should be larger.
